@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node RUNNING
@prev MAIN
@next FORMAT
@toc MAIN
@{r}.asm inline assembler

@{c}@{h1}Running .asm

There are two main ways to run @{b}.asm@{ub}:

 * from within a NextBASIC program, or
 * from the command line.

@{h2}From within a NextBASIC program

Here, @{b}.asm@{ub} is run from inside a program as a command, for example:

  10 SAVE "asmprint.bas" : REM Just in case things go wrong
  20 CLEAR $bfff : REM Move RAMTOP so we have some space for our code
  30 @{b}.asm@{ub} : REM Assemble our code
  40 ;@{i}    ld a, 2@{ui}
  50 ;@{i}    call $1601@{ui}
  60 ;@{i}loop@{ui}
  70 ;@{i}    ld de, msg@{ui}
  80 ;@{i}    ld bc, eom-msg@{ui}
  90 ;@{i}    call $203c@{ui}
 100 ;@{i}    jr loop@{ui}
 110 ;@{i}msg db "Hello World", 13@{ui}
 120 ;@{i}eom equ $@{ui}
 130 RANDOMIZE USR ($c000) : REM Call our machine code routine

@{b}.asm@{ub} will detect the line from which it is being run and begin assembly from the
following line (in the above example, this is line 40).

Lines of the assembly language program are marked with leading '@{b};@{ub}' (semicolon)
characters and continue until the first line which does NOT begin with a '@{b};@{ub}' (up
to and including line 120, above).  The semicolon character normally marks a
comment in a NextBASIC program (the same as @{b}REM@{ub}) so would otherwise be ignored.

When used in this mode, the @{" LET " LINK LET} @{" pseudo operation " LINK PSEUDO_OPS} is useful to feed addresses
from the assembled code back into the containing program.

@{h2}From the command line

@{b}.asm@{ub} can also be run directly from the command line (including in immediate mode
in NextBASIC - a command entered without a line number).

In this situation, the program to be assembled is provided in a file and the
name of that file supplied as an argument on the command line.

The file must be in plain text, consisting of just the assembly lanugage code
(and any labels or pseudo operations), without BASIC line numbers.  Assembly
will stop at the end of the file.

See also: @{" INCLUDE " LINK INCLUDE}, @{" OUTPUT " LINK OUTPUT}, @{" Program format " LINK FORMAT}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node FORMAT
@prev RUNNING
@next LABELS
@toc MAIN
@{r}.asm inline assembler

@{c}@{h1}Program format

Lines of assembly in NextBASIC programs using @{b}.asm@{ub} have the form:

 @{i}line-number@{ui} @{b};@{ub}[@{i}label@{ui}[@{b}:@{ub}]][ @{i}operation@{ui}]

The '@{b};@{ub}' character is part of NextBASIC itself and indicates a comment (same as
@{b}REM@{ub}), so NextBASIC itself won't try and execute the line (see @{" running .asm " LINK RUNNING}).

If a @{" label " LINK LABELS} is specified on a line, it must appear at the beginning, without
any leading spaces between '@{b};@{ub}' and it.  It can optionally be followed by a
trailing '@{b}:@{ub}' (colon).

Instructions or @{" pseudo operations " LINK PSEUDO_OPS} can appear after a label (with intervening
space) or on a separate line.  If on a separate line, there must be one or more
leading spaces, to indicate it is not a label.

Assembly instructions can be in lower or upper case.

When assembly is read from a plain text file by running @{b}.asm@{ub} from the
@{" command line " LINK RUNNING}, or using the @{" INCLUDE " LINK INCLUDE} pseudo operation, the @{i}line-number@{ui} and '@{b};@{ub}'
are omitted.
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node LABELS
@prev FORMAT
@next EXPRESSIONS
@toc MAIN
@{r}.asm inline assembler

@{c}@{h1}Labels

The assembler supports three main types of label:

 * global labels
 * local labels
 * anonymous labels

Labels can be used as operands to assembly instructions (for example, as a jump
destination address), or as values in an @{" expression " LINK EXPRESSIONS}.

A label is identified as such, and not an instruction or @{" pseudo operation " LINK PSEUDO_OPS} by
appearing at the beginning of a line, with no leading spaces.

A label can optionally be followed by a '@{b}:@{ub}' for readability, but this has no
effect on the name.  Label names are case-insensitive.

@{h2}Global labels

Global labels have names beginning with a letter '@{b}a@{ub}' to '@{b}z@{ub}' and are scoped to
the entire program so can be referenced from anywhere directly.

The entire name has the following format, limited to a maximum of 15 characters
in total:

 {@{b}a@{ub}..@{b}z@{ub}}{@{b}.@{ub} @{b}_@{ub} @{b}a@{ub}..@{b}z@{ub} @{b}0@{ub}..@{b}9@{ub}}*                (* = zero or more occurrences)

@{h2}Local labels

Local labels have names beginning with a dot/period ('@{b}.@{ub}') and are and are scoped
to the block that starts with the previous global label (or beginning of the
code) and ends with the next global label.

The entire name has the format:

 @{b}.@{ub}{@{b}.@{ub} @{b}_@{ub} @{b}a@{ub}..@{b}z@{ub} @{b}0@{ub}..@{b}9@{ub}}+                     (+ = one or more occurrences)

The entire name, including the global label used at the beginning of the scope,
is limited to 15 characters.

Within its scope, a name can be used directly (with the leading '@{b}.@{ub}').  To use a
local label from another scope, it must be referenced using the block's starting
global label, then the local part (including '@{b}.@{ub}').

Local labels allow the reuse of local addresses for loops or to jump to other
parts of the same block, without worrying about the name clashing with another
part of the entire program.

@{h2}Anonymous labels

An anonymous label has the name '@{b}_@{ub}' (with no trailing characters).

The label can be referenced using two forms:

 * '@{b}-_@{ub}' points to the previous anonymous label
 * '@{b}+_@{ub}' points to the next anonymous label

Anonymous labels are not limited to a block delimited by global labels, but only
the previous or next label can be referenced, so are only suitable for skipping
short blocks, or jumping back to the start of the current loop.
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node EXPRESSIONS
@prev LABELS
@next PSEUDO_OPS
@toc MAIN
@{r}.asm inline assembler

@{c}@{h1}Expressions

In all places where the assembler accepts a value, an expression can be used to
calculate the number.

@{h2}Values in an expression

An expression can make use of various values in calculating an expression:

 * literal values
 * @{" labels " LINK LABELS} - corresponding to the address of the label)
 * '@{b}$@{ub}' - the current instruction address / program counter
 * '@{b}%@{ub}@{i}var@{ui}' - NextBASIC integer variable values

@{h2}Operators and precedence

The assembler follows the normal BODMAS/PEMDAS operator precedence rules.
Operators at the same precedence are evaluated left to right, sub-expressions
within parentheses are evaluated before all other operators.

Available operators are given in the table below, from high to low precedence:

 Operator(s)   Description
 -----------   --------------------------------------------
 @{b}(@{ub}...@{b})@{ub}         Parenthesised sub-expressions
 @{b}~@{ub},@{b}!@{ub},@{b}+@{ub},@{b}-@{ub}       Complement, logical NOT, unary plus/minus
 @{b}*@{ub},@{b}/@{ub},@{b}%@{ub}         Multiplication, division, modulo (remainder)
 @{b}+@{ub},@{b}-@{ub}           Addition, subtraction
 @{b}<<@{ub},@{b}>>@{ub}         Bitwise shift
 @{b}<@{ub},@{b}<=@{ub},@{b}>@{ub},@{b}>=@{ub}     Relational operators
 @{b}=@{ub},@{b}<>@{ub}          Equal, not equal
 @{b}&@{ub}             Bitwise AND
 @{b}^@{ub}             Bitwise XOR
 @{b}|@{ub}             Bitwise OR
 @{b}&&@{ub}            Logical AND
 @{b}||@{ub}            Logical OR

See also: @{" EQU " LINK EQU}, @{" LET " LINK LET}, @{" VAR " LINK VAR}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node PSEUDO_OPS
@prev EXPRESSIONS
@next ALIGN
@toc MAIN
@{r}.asm inline assembler

@{c}@{h1}Pseudo operations

 Operation         Meaning
 ---------------   -----------------------------------------------------
 @{" ALIGN " LINK ALIGN}           Aligns next instruction to a boundary
 @{" ASSERT " LINK ASSERT}          Raise error if an expression evaluates to false
 @{" BANK " LINK BANK}            Assemble directly to banked memory
 @{" BRK " LINK BRK}             Insert CSpect BREAK instruction
 @{" DB " LINK DX}              Define byte(s)
 @{" DC " LINK DX}              Define string(s) terminated with high bit set
 @{" DS " LINK DX}              Define space, all set to 0
 @{" DW " LINK DX}              Define 16-bit word(s)
 @{" DZ " LINK DX}              Define string(s) terminated with 0 byte
 @{" DISPLAY " LINK DISPLAY}         Display information during assembly
 @{" EQU " LINK EQU}             Define a constant
 @{" IF/ELSE/ENDIF " LINK IF}   Conditional assembly
 @{" INCLUDE " LINK INCLUDE}         Include a text file during assembly
 @{" LET " LINK LET}             Set the value of a NextBASIC integer variable
 @{" NBRK " LINK NBRK}            Insert hardware breakpoint, triggering Next debugger
 @{" ORG " LINK ORG}             Set the base address for label calculation
 @{" OUTPUT " LINK OUTPUT}          Write assembled code to a file
 @{" RELOC_COUNT " LINK RELOC}     Return the number of relocations tracked.
 @{" RELOC_END " LINK RELOC}       Mark the end of a relocation block.
 @{" RELOC_START " LINK RELOC}     Mark the start of a relocation block.
 @{" RELOC_TABLE " LINK RELOC}     Emit a relocation table.
 @{" SAVENEX " LINK SAVENEX}         Save a block of memory as a ".nex" file.
 @{" VAR " LINK VAR}             Declare a named value to be variable.
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node ALIGN
@prev PSEUDO_OPS
@next ASSERT
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}ALIGN

Pseudo operation to align the address of the next instruction:

  @{b}ALIGN@{ub} @{i}bytes@{ui}

Aligns the next instruction to an address of multiple @{i}bytes@{ui}.  If an adjustment
is required, the gap is padded with zeroes.

@{i}bytes@{ui} must be a power of 2.

See also: @{" DS (define) " LINK DX}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node ASSERT
@prev ALIGN
@next BANK
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}ASSERT

Abort assemly if an expression evaluates to false:

  @{b}ASSERT@{ub} @{i}expr@{ui}

Evaluates the @{" expression " LINK EXPRESSIONS} @{i}expr@{ui} - if it results in a false (zero) value an
@{i}Assertion false@{ui} error is raised and assembly stopped.

See also: @{" IF ... ELSE ... ENDIF " LINK IF}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node BANK
@prev ASSERT
@next BRK
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}BANK

Set the target bank and offset for assembler output:

 @{b}BANK@{ub} @{i}bank@{ui}[,[@{i}offset@{ui}]][,[@{i}clear@{ui}]]

Assembles code to bank number @{i}bank@{ui} at the optional address @{i}offset@{ui} from the
beginning - if omitted, assembly will start at offset 0.

If @{i}clear@{ui} is set to true (a non-zero value), the bank's 16KByte of memory will be
cleared first.

Code assembled in this way can be run from NextBASIC using the @{b}BANK@{ub} ... @{b}USR@{ub}
function:

  @{i}val@{ui} = @{b}BANK@{ub} @{i}bank@{ui} @{b}USR@{ub} @{i}offset@{ui}

Note that this function will page in the bank at address 49152 ($c000), which is
the same as the default value for @{" ORG " LINK ORG}.

If using @{" LET " LINK LET} to return addresses into NextBASIC integer variables, care should
be taken to adjust for offsets addressing, when using the @{b}BANK@{ub} operation.

See also: @{" OUTPUT " LINK OUTPUT}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node BRK
@prev BANK
@next DX
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}BRK

Insert a CSpect BREAK instruction:

 @{b}BRK@{ub}

This will trigger the CSpect emulator to break into the debugger.

See also: @{" ASSERT " LINK ASSERT}, @{" NBRK " LINK NBRK}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node DX
@prev BRK
@next DISPLAY
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}Dx (define)

Define a block of data:

 @{b}DB@{ub} @{i}b1|s1@{ui}[,@{i}s2|b2@{ui}[,...]]
 @{b}DC@{ub} @{i}s1@{ui}[,@{i}s2@{ui}[,...]]
 @{b}DS@{ub} @{i}n@{ui}
 @{b}DW@{ub} @{i}w1@{ui}[,@{i}w2@{ui}[,...]]
 @{b}DZ@{ub} @{i}s1@{ui}[,@{i}s2@{ui}[,...]]

The @{b}D@{ub}@{i}x@{ui} pseudo operations allow data to be inserted into the code.

@{h2}DB - Define Byte(s)

When given an integer, a byte of that value will be inserted into the generated
code.  If a string is provided, the character codes for the bytes in the string
will be inserted directly; no terminating character or mark will be added.

A list of values can be supplied to store multiple bytes.  Integers and strings
can be mixed in a single statement.

@{h2}DC - Define Character(s)

Similar to @{b}DB@{ub} but only accepting string arguments.  The final character in each
string will have the high bit set (+128/$80).

@{h2}DS - Define Space

Defines a block of @{i}n@{ui} bytes, initialised to 0.

@{h2}DW - Define Word(s)

Defines a list of 16-bit words, little endian (least significant byte first).

@{h2}DZ - Define Zero-terminated String(s)

This is similar to @{b}DB@{ub} and @{b}DC@{ub}, except that each string will be terminated by a 0
byte.

See also: @{" ALIGN " LINK ALIGN}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node DISPLAY
@prev DX
@next EQU
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}DISPLAY

Display information during the assembly process:

 @{b}DISPLAY@{ub} {@{i}str@{ui}|@{i}expr@{ui}|@{b}/D@{ub}|@{b}/H@{ub}|@{b}/B@{ub}|@{b}/C@{ub}[,...]}

Displays strings and/or the result of numeric @{" expressions " LINK EXPRESSIONS} during the assembly
process.

The format for displaying numbers can be altered with switches:

 Switch   Format
 ------   -------------------------------------------------------------------
 @{b}/D@{ub}       Decimal mode (default).
 @{b}/H@{ub}       Hexadecimal mode - 2 digits for <=255/$ff, 4 digits for >=256/$100.
 @{b}/B@{ub}       Binary mode - 8 bits for <=255/$ff, 16 bits for >=256/$100.
 @{b}/C@{ub}       Character mode - uses the least significant byte as an ASCII value.

When the format is changed, it will stay in effect until altered again.
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node EQU
@prev DISPLAY
@next IF
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}EQU

Define a constant:

 @{i}name@{ui} @{b}EQU@{ub} @{i}expr@{ui}

Defines the constant @{i}name@{ui} to the numeric value of the result of evaluating the
@{" expression " LINK EXPRESSIONS} @{i}expr@{ui}.

See also: @{" LET " LINK LET}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node IF
@prev EQU
@next INCLUDE
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}IF ... ELSE ... ENDIF

Assemble a block of code conditionally:

 @{b}IF@{ub} @{i}condition@{ui}
  ...
 [@{b}ELSE@{ub}
  ...]
 @{b}ENDIF@{ub}

If the result of evaluating the @{" expression " LINK EXPRESSIONS} @{i}condition@{ui} is true (non-zero), the
block of code following the @{b}IF@{ub} statement is assembled, otherwise the block of
code following @{b}ELSE@{ub} is assembled, if present.

Conditional code blocks can be nested up to 7 levels deep.

Note that @{b}IF@{ub} is an assembly-time choice - it cannot be used to choose
alternative code blocks at runtime.

See also: @{" ASSERT " LINK ASSERT}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node INCLUDE
@prev IF
@next LET
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}INCLUDE

Include code from a separate file:

 @{b}INCLUDE@{ub} "@{i}filename@{ui}"

Includes the code from the file @{i}filename@{ui} in the assembly.  @{b}INCLUDE@{ub} can nest up
to 8 levels deep, with no strict limit on the number of files that can be
included.

The included files are stored as plain text, without line numbers, or leading
semicolons but, otherwise, must be in a format supported by the assembler in a
NextBASIC program.

See also: @{" OUTPUT " LINK OUTPUT}, @{" Program format " LINK FORMAT}, @{" Running .asm " LINK RUNNING}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node LET
@prev INCLUDE
@next NBRK
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}LET

Assign a value to a NextBASIC integer variable:

 @{b}LET@{ub} @{i}var@{ui}=@{i}expr@{ui}

Assigns the result of evaluating numeric @{" expression " LINK EXPRESSIONS} @{i}expr@{ui} to the variable @{i}var@{ui}.
@{i}var@{ui} must be a NextBASIC integer variable (one with a leading '@{b}%@{ub}' character).

This function is useful to return the location of addresses in the assembled
code, to be used by the surrounding program.

@{h2}Address considerations when using BANK

When assembling directly into banked memory, using the @{" BANK " LINK BANK} pseudo operation,
returned addresses will need to be adjusted, if using offset instructions in
NextBASIC.

For example, the first address in a banked block will be 49152 (the address the
code will be paged in at, when run).  If, however, an instruction such as @{b}BANK@{ub}
@{i}bank@{ui} @{b}USR@{ub} @{i}offset@{ui} is used to execute code, 49152 will need to be subtracted from
the address returned with @{b}LET@{ub}.

See also: @{" EQU " LINK EQU}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node NBRK
@prev LET
@next ORG
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}NBRK

Insert a hardware breakpoint:

 @{b}NBRK@{ub}

This will trigger the NextZXOS debugger, equivalent to the assembly instruction
@{b}NEXTREG 2,8@{ub} (or @{b}REG 2,8@{ub} in NextBASIC).

See also: @{" ASSERT " LINK ASSERT}, @{" BRK " LINK BRK}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node ORG
@prev NBRK
@next OUTPUT
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}ORG

Set the address at that point in assembly:

 @{b}ORG@{ub} @{i}addr@{ui}

The behaviour of @{b}ORG@{ub} depends on the target specified for assembled code,
controlled by the @{" BANK " LINK BANK} and @{" OUTPUT " LINK OUTPUT} pseudo operations.

The default is to assemble to address 49152 ($c000).

@{h2}Main memory

If neither @{b}BANK@{ub} nor @{b}OUTPUT@{ub} have been specified, @{b}ORG@{ub} assembles code to main
memory at @{i}addr@{ui}.

To avoid corrupting memory used by NextBASIC, the @{b}CLEAR@{ub} command should be used
with a value lower than @{i}addr@{ui}, to protect the memory above it.

@{h2}Banked memory

If the @{b}BANK@{ub} pseudo operation has been specified, code is assembled to the bank
and offset specified with that operation; @{b}ORG@{ub} will, however, set the base
address used to calculate labels to @{i}addr@{ui}.

@{h2}Output to a file

If the @{b}OUTPUT@{ub} pseudo operation has been used, code will be written to the
specified file, but the base address used for calculating labels will be set to
@{i}addr@{ui}.
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node OUTPUT
@prev ORG
@next RELOC
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}OUTPUT

Write assembled code to a file:

 @{b}OUTPUT@{ub} "@{i}filename@{ui}"

Directs the assembler to write the generated machine code directly to a file
specified by @{i}filename@{ui}.

See also: @{" BANK " LINK BANK}, @{" INCLUDE " LINK INCLUDE}, @{" ORG " LINK ORG}, @{" SAVENEX " LINK SAVENEX}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node RELOC
@prev OUTPUT
@next SAVENEX
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}RELOC_x (relocation table)

Generate relocation information for NextZXOS drivers:

 @{b}RELOC_COUNT@{ub}
 @{b}RELOC_END@{ub}
 @{b}RELOC_START@{ub}
 @{b}RELOC_TABLE@{ub}

A block of code can be marked with the @{b}RELOC_START@{ub} and @{b}RELOC_END@{ub} pseudo
operations to track relocations.

@{b}RELOC_COUNT@{ub} will return the number of relocations in tracked code in a tracked
block.

@{b}RELOC_TABLE@{ub} will emit the relocation block.  The table is a raw dump of the high
byte of every address that will need to be patched to relocate the code.  The
format of this table is specifically designed to support the creation of
NextZXOS drivers.
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node SAVENEX
@prev RELOC
@next VAR
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}SAVENEX

Generate a ".nex" file from the assembled code:

 @{b}SAVENEX@{ub} "@{i}filename@{ui}",@{i}start-addr@{ui},@{i}stack-addr@{ui}[,@{i}required-ram@{ui}[,@{i}entry-bank@{ui}]]

The @{b}SAVENEX@{ub} pseudo operation should be used after code has been assembled to
write out ...

TODO

@{i}start-addr@{ui} is start of block to save; end is PC ($)?

@{i}stack-addr@{ui} is top of stack, so ample space below this address must be reserved
by the code with @{" DS " LINK DX}.

@{i}required-ram@{ui}?

@{i}entry-bank@{ui}?

See also: @{" OUTPUT " LINK OUTPUT}
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node VAR
@prev SAVENEX
@next INDEX
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}Pseudo operations

@{c}@{h1}VAR

Declares a named value to be variable between passes:

 @{b}VAR@{ub} @{i}expr@{ui}

When assembling code with @{" expressions " LINK EXPRESSIONS} that vary between passes (typically by
using a label which occurs later in the code), the assembler will abort with a
@{i}Value changed@{ui} error.  The @{b}VAR@{ub} pseudo operation will avoid this.

Typically @{b}VAR@{ub} will be used with an @{i}expr@{ui} of '@{b}$@{ub}' (for the current address).

Once a value is declared as a variable with @{b}VAR@{ub}, that property will propagate
through to all places where it is used (e.g. if the value is used in an @{" EQU " LINK EQU}
calculation, this will be variable).
@-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node INDEX
@prev VAR
@toc PSEUDO_OPS
@{r}.asm inline assembler

